openai.summary:
De flesta dimensionstabeller (GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDMI FLEX) i grafen matchar PDF numeriskt för flöden, vikter och storlekslistor, och produktfamiljerna som listas i PDF (GDP, GDB, GDMI, GDC, GDC FLEX, GDMI FLEX, BFF, PFF, PT, TT, EXL, Filter Profil) finns i grafen. Den största dataintegritetsrisken är i GDC FLEX där en WxH-inversion gör att storleksnycklar (och därmed patronantal och rekommenderade flöden) kan vara knutna till fel dimension. Detta är CRITICAL eftersom det direkt påverkar produktval.

Nästa största avvikelse är att grafen introducerar icke-PDF-data (Max Chlorine PPM) som kan påverka rekommendationslogik men saknar stöd i katalogen. Slutligen finns flera format-/modellbrister: kodformat för Filter Profil saknar djup, EXL-kodformat är tvetydigt (mellanslag vs bindestreck), anslutningstyp (PG vs fläns/F40) är inte modellerad som en riktig valbar feature trots att PDF uttryckligen beskriver detta och att längd anges som PG/F40-intervall i flera familjer. Åtgärderna ovan bör ge en graf som är både PDF-trogen och maskinellt robust.

anthropic_opus.summary:
The Knowledge Graph demonstrates a high degree of fidelity to the PDF catalog. All 12 product families are present, and the vast majority of dimensional data, weights, airflow ratings, cartridge counts, and material availability are accurately captured. The graph contains 273 dimension modules covering all sizes listed across all product families in the PDF, with no missing sizes detected.

The most notable issues are: (1) A potential module count error for GDB 600x900 where the ¼/½/1 breakdown appears to be 0/1/1 in the graph but should be 1/0/1 per the PDF table; (2) The GDMI FLEX weight column header duplication in the PDF (both labeled 1100/1150) is properly flagged as a source conflict; (3) The GDB 1800x900 anomalous weight of 36 kg is correctly flagged as a suspected PDF error; (4) The GDC FLEX size label vs. table column inconsistency for the 600x300 entry needs manufacturer verification. The graph commendably documents source conflicts and suspected PDF errors rather than silently resolving them.

Overall, the graph earns a score of 72/100, reflecting strong data completeness and accuracy with appropriate handling of PDF ambiguities. The deductions are primarily for the module count discrepancy, the unresolved material default question for GDMI, and some minor metadata gaps around construction details. The graph's approach of flagging source conflicts is exemplary and should be maintained as the catalog evolves.

final_report.summary:
The knowledge graph demonstrates strong structural fidelity to the MANN+HUMMEL HVAC Filterskåp PDF catalog (Version 01-09-2025). All 12 product families listed in the table of contents are represented, and the vast majority of dimensional data across 273+ dimension modules is accurately captured. Spot-checks of sizes, weights, airflow ratings, cartridge counts, and filter module breakdowns across GDP (35 sizes), GDB (27 sizes), GDMI (37 sizes), GDC (12 sizes), GDC FLEX (6 sizes), GDMI FLEX (8 sizes), BFF (5 sizes), PFF (25 sizes), PT (5 sizes), TT (35 sizes), EXL (8 sizes), and Filter Profil (36 combinations) show near-complete numerical accuracy.

The most significant issues fall into three categories: (1) Data completeness gaps — specific filter SKUs and accessory products from the FILTER & TILLBEHÖR sections are entirely absent from the graph, and the PTT/PT naming alias is missing; (2) Unresolved PDF ambiguities — the GDMI and GDMI FLEX families have conflicting default material signals (text says ZM, example codes use AZ/FZ), and the GDC FLEX dimension table has an inconsistency between size labels and Bredd/Höjd columns that could cause incorrect product selection; (3) Modeling gaps — connection type (PG vs F40) is not modeled as a selectable feature despite affecting physical length, filter type compatibility constraints are not machine-readable, and non-PDF engineering data (chlorine PPM) is mixed with catalog data without clear provenance separation.

The graph commendably flags known PDF errors (GDB 1800x900 weight typo, GDMI FLEX weight column mislabeling, GDMI length variant text-vs-table conflict) rather than silently resolving them. The overall score of 76 reflects a graph that is reliable for dimensional lookups and basic product selection but requires targeted improvements in SKU-level completeness, material default resolution, and feature modeling before it can serve as a robust engineering configurator backend.
